# Backend Design Patterns Rules

## 1. Dependency Injection (DI)

- All dependencies must be injected, never instantiated directly inside business logic.
- Use constructor injection as the default approach.
- The composition root is responsible for wiring dependencies.
- Business logic must depend on abstractions (interfaces), not concrete implementations.

---

## 2. Repository Pattern

- All data access must go through repository interfaces.
- Repositories belong to the Domain or Application layer (as interfaces).
- Implementations belong to the Infrastructure layer.
- Domain/Application layers must never access databases directly.

---

## 3. Factory Pattern

- Use factories when object creation logic is complex or conditional.
- Factories are responsible for encapsulating creation rules.
- Domain objects should not contain complex instantiation logic.

---

## 4. Strategy Pattern

- Use Strategy when behavior must be interchangeable at runtime.
- Strategies must implement a shared interface.
- Selection of strategy must be external to the business logic.

---

## 5. Encapsulation Rule

- Internal implementation details must not leak between layers.
- Each module must expose only its intended public interface.
- Avoid exposing internal domain logic through infrastructure or presentation layers.

---

## 6. Composition Over Inheritance

- Prefer composition for behavior reuse.
- Inheritance is allowed only for strict domain hierarchies where behavior is stable and well-defined.

---

## 7. Pure Domain Rule

- Domain logic must remain free of infrastructure concerns.
- No database, API, or framework code is allowed inside domain logic.